.SH NAME
lambda-cli \- plain command-line lambda calculus beta reducer
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lambda-cli
.RI [ OPTION ...]
.RI [ EXPR ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lambda-cli
reduces lambda calculus expressions from command-line arguments. If no
expression is supplied, it reads expressions line by line from standard input.
.PP
Expressions use normal-order beta reduction. Final result lines are numbered
as
.BR [N]> .
Across expressions in one invocation or standard-input session,
.B %
refers to the previous numbered output result and
.BI % N
refers to numbered output line
.IR N .
A trailing
.B /
or
.BI / N
performs gradual reduction by one or
.I N
steps; a displayed
.B (...)
means more beta steps remain.
.PP
This command is the minimal non-ncurses front end. Use
.BR lambda (1)
for the interactive definition table and ncurses interface.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-e,\ --eval\  EXPR
Reduce
.IR EXPR .
.TP
.BI --max-steps\  N
Stop reducing after
.I N
steps. The default is 300.
.TP
.B \-h, --help
Show usage information.
.TP
.B \-V, --version
Show version information.
.SH SYNTAX
.TP
.B \ex.x
Abstraction. Backslash and the UTF-8 lambda character are both accepted.
.TP
.B x y z
Application. Application is left associative, so this means
.BR "(x y) z" .
.TP
.B f \ex.x
Bare lambda abstractions may be used as application arguments. This means
.BR "f (\ex.x)" .
.TP
.B xx
Lowercase letters split into variables, so this means
.BR "x x" .
.TP
.B x1 x2
Subscript-style variables.
.TP
.B %
Previous numbered output result.
History references are reserved and cannot be lambda parameters.
.TP
.BI % N
Result from numbered output line
.IR N .
.TP
.B TERM /
Reduce
.I TERM
by one beta step and stop.
.TP
.BI TERM\ / N
Reduce
.I TERM
by
.I N
beta steps and stop.
.TP
.BI / N
Continue the previous gradual reduction by
.I N
steps. A bare
.B /
or empty input continues by one step.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
.B lambda-cli '(\ex.x) y'
Reduce an expression and print each step.
.TP
.B printf '%s\en' '(\ex.x) y' | lambda-cli
Read expressions from standard input.
